# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tryptophan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was first reported by Henri Victor Regnault in 1840.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Industrially, it is usually produced in a two-step process from vinyl chloride.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction is catalyzed by a variety of Lewis acids, mainly aluminium chloride, iron(III) chloride, or zinc chloride.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction proceeds at 80%–90% yield, and the hydrogen chloride byproduct can be recycled to the first step in the process.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The major side-product is the related compound 1,1,2-trichloroethane, from which the 1,1,1-trichloroethane can be separated by distillation.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is sold with stabilizers because it is unstable with respect to dehydrochlorination and attacks some metals.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Stabilizers comprise up to 8% of the formulation, including acid scavengers (epoxides, amines) and complexants.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] One discontinued product contained only 1,4-dioxane (2%±1%), while another chemical supplier included 2.5% 1,4-dioxane, 0.47% 1,2-butylene oxide, and 0.35% nitromethane as stabilizers.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is an excellent solvent for many organic compounds and one of the least toxic of the chlorinated hydrocarbons.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is generally considered non-polar, but owing to the good polarizability of the chlorine atoms, it is a superior solvent for organic compounds that do not dissolve well in hydrocarbons such as hexane.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Prior to the Montreal Protocol, it was widely used for cleaning metal parts and circuit boards, as a photoresist solvent in the electronics industry, as an aerosol propellant, as a cutting fluid additive, and as a solvent for inks, paints, adhesives, and other coatings.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used to dry-clean leather and suede.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Use in dry-cleaning remained until the 1980s.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used as an insecticidal fumigant.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also the standard cleaner for photographic film.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Other commonly available solvents damage emulsion and base (acetone will dissolve triacetate base on most films), and thus are not suitable for this application.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The standard replacement, Forane 141 is much less effective, and tends to leave a residue.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also used as a thinner in correction fluid products such as liquid paper.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Many of its applications previously used carbon tetrachloride (which was banned in US consumer products in 1970).
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In turn, 1,1,1-trichloroethane itself is now being replaced by other solvents in the laboratory.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Phase-out of 1,1,1-Trichloroethane due to ozone depletion lead to a resurgence of the use of trichloroethylene in metal degreasing.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Methyl chloroform was also used as a veterinary anthelmintic.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was one of the volatile organochlorides that have been tried as alternatives to chloroform in anaesthesia.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In the 1880s, it was found to be a safe and strong substitute for chloroform but its production was too expensive and difficult for the era.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In 1880, 1,1,1-trichloroethane was suggested as an anaesthetic.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was first referred to as methyl-chloroform in the same year.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] At the time, the narcotic effects of chloral hydrate were owed to a hypothetical metabolic pathway to chloroform in "alkaline blood".
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Trichloroethane was studied for its structural similarity to chloral and potential anaesthetic effects.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] However, trichloroethane did not exhibit any conversion to chloroform in laboratory experiments.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The 1,1,2-Trichloroethane (vinyl trichloride) isomer, which lacked a trichloromethyl group, exhibited anaesthetic effects even stronger than the 1,1,1 isomer.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The International Agency for Research on Cancer places 1,1,1-trichloroethane in Group 2A as a probable carcinogen.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is a fairly potent greenhouse gas with a 100-year global warming potential of 169 relative to carbon dioxide.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This is nonetheless less than a tenth that of carbon tetrachloride — which it replaced as a solvent — due to its relatively short atmospheric lifetime of about 5 years.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The Montreal Protocol targeted 1,1,1-trichloroethane as a compound responsible for ozone depletion and banned its use beginning in 1996.
[src:tryptophan/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Since then, its manufacture and use have been phased out throughout most of the world, and its atmospheric concentration has declined substantially.
[src:tryptophan/1-api] α-Methylisotryptamine is a monoamine releasing agent and serotonin receptor agonist of the isotryptamine group.
[src:tryptophan/1-api] It is the isotryptamine homologue of α-methyltryptamine (αMT), which is a more well-known serotonergic psychedelic, entactogen, and stimulant of the tryptamine family with similar pharmacological actions.
[src:tryptophan/1-api] Like αMT, α-methylisotryptamine is a monoamine releasing agent.
[src:tryptophan/1-api] As the (–)-enantiomer, it specifically acts as a preferential serotonin and norepinephrine releasing agent (SNRA), with EC50Tooltip half-maximal effective concentration values of 177 nM for serotonin release, 81 nM for norepinephrine release, and 1,062 nM for dopamine release.
[src:tryptophan/1-api] In addition to its monoamine release, α-methylisotryptamine shows affinity for serotonin 5-HT2 receptors.
[src:tryptophan/1-api] A derivative of α-methylisotryptamine, zalsupindole (DLX-001; AAZ-A-154; (*R*)-5-MeO-*N*,*N*-dimethyl-isoAMT), is a non-hallucinogenic serotonin 5-HT2A receptor agonist and is being developed for potential medical use in the treatment depression and other neuropsychiatric disorders.
[src:tryptophan/1-api] Other derivatives of α-methylisotryptamine have also been developed, such as the selective serotonin 5-HT2C receptor agonists (*S*)-5,6-difluoro-isoAMT and Ro60-0175 ((*S*)-5-fluoro-6-chloro-isoAMT), among others.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine is currently used as an antitussive agent in Iceland, as well as Romania, Bulgaria, Russia and other Eastern European countries.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Bulgarian pharmaceutical company Sopharma sells glaucine in tablet form, where a single dose contains 40 mg.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] It is known to be sold over-the-counter.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Reports of recreational use of glaucine have been published, and effects include dissociative-type symptoms; feeling detached and "in another world, as well as nausea, vomiting, and dilated pupils.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] These reports mirror those about the effects of clinical use, which state dissociative-type symptoms as well as lethargy, fatigue, and hallucinations.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Investigation of side effects in a clinical setting also reports that the hallucinatory effects manifest as bright and colorful visualizations.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] They further report that patients perceive their environments clearly yet feel detached from it; "the patient sees and understands everything and is oriented well enough, but cannot take a clear and adequate action".
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] One particular report of recreational use gone awry described the form of distribution as tablets being marketed as a 1-benzylpiperazine (BZP)-free "herbal high" which the patient referred to as "head candy".
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine may produce side effects such as sedation, sleepiness, fatigue, weakness, nausea, pupil dilation, and hallucinogenic effects such as visual hallucinations and dissociation.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine binds to the benzothiazepine site on L-type Ca2+-channels, thereby blocking calcium ion channels in smooth muscle like the human bronchus.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine has no effect on intracellular calcium stores, but rather, does not allow the entry of Ca2+ after intracellular stores have been depleted.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Ca2+ influx is a vital component in the process of muscular contraction, and the blocking of this influx therefore reduces the ability of the muscle to contract.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] In this way, glaucine can prevent smooth muscle from contracting, allowing it to relax.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] It is a non-competitive selective inhibitor of PDE4 in human bronchial tissue and granulocytes.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] PDE4 is an isoenzyme that hydrolyzes cyclic AMP to regulate human bronchial tone (along with PDE3).
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Yet as a PDE4 inhibitor, glaucine possesses very low potency.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine has been found to act on the serotonin 5-HT2 receptors.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] (*S*)-Glaucine is partial agonist of the serotonin 5-HT2A and 5-HT2C receptors, whereas (*R*)-glaucine is a positive allosteric modulator of the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor and possibly of the other two serotonin 5-HT2 receptors.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] At the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor, (*S*)-glaucine showed an affinity (Ki) of 966 nM, EC50Tooltip half-maximal effective concentration of 661 nM, and an EmaxTooltip maximal efficacy of 42%, whereas at the serotonin 5-HT2C receptor, it displayed an EC50 of 447 nM and an Emax of 52%.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Activation of the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor is notably known to be responsible for the hallucinogenic effects of serotonergic psychedelics like psilocybin, LSD, and mescaline.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] However, while activation of the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor may be involved, the underlying mechanism of action responsible for the hallucinogenic effects of glaucine remains unknown.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine also shows affinity for the serotonin 5-HT1A and 5-HT7 receptors (Ki = 171 nM and 43 nM, respectively).
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Both (*R*)-glaucine and (*S*)-glaucine antagonize the α1-adrenergic receptor.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine has been demonstrated to be a dopamine receptor antagonist, favoring dopamine D1 and D1-like receptors.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Besides actions on monoamine receptors, glaucine inhibits monoamine oxidase A (MAO-A), but its IC50Tooltip half-maximal inhibitory concentration could not be determined due to solubility issues.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] It has bronchodilator, neuroleptic, and antiinflammatory effects, acting as a PDE4 inhibitor and calcium channel blocker, TLRs plays role in its anti inflammatory effects.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine has been reported to reduce blood pressure and heart rate and to possess anticonvulsant and antinociceptive effects in animals.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] The pharmacokinetics of glaucine have been studied in humans and in horses.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] In addition, the *in-vitro* human metabolism of glaucine has been studied.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine is a racemic mixture of (*S*)- and (*R*)- enantiomers.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] (*S*)-Glaucine is the form that mainly occurs in nature.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] However, while it was originally believed that only (*S*)-glaucine occurs in nature, (*R*)-glaucine has since been found in fire poppy (*Papaver californicum)*.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] The form used in medicine appears to exclusively be the (*S*) enantiomer and not the racemic mixture or (*R*)- enantiomer.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] The chemical synthesis of glaucine has been described.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Analogues of glaucine include other aporphine alkaloids like apomorphine, boldine, bulbocapnine, nantenine, nuciferine, and pukateine, among many others.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Certain synthetic analogues of glaucine such as 2-hydroxy-11-(2-methylallyl)oxynoraporphine are known to act as highly potent and high-efficacy serotonin 5-HT2A and 5-HT2C receptor agonists.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Probst via isolation from *Glaucium flavum* (yellow horned poppy) in 1839.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] However, its chemical identity was not elucidated until later by other researchers, such as Richard Fischer in 1901 (chemical formula) and J.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] The drug subsequently came to be used medically as an antitussive (cough suppressant) in some Eastern European countries.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine was reported to produce hallucinogenic effects in 1989.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Later, it was reported as a novel designer recreational drug in 2008.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] The drug was found to act as a serotonin 5-HT2A receptor partial agonist and positive allosteric modulator in 2019.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] Glaucine is marketed for use as an antitussive (cough suppressant) in Bulgaria, Croatia, and Romania.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] When ingested orally has been found to increase airway conductance in humans, and has been investigated as a treatment for asthma.
[src:tryptophan/r-glaucine] The bronchodilator activity of glaucine is thought to be related to its phosphodiesterase PDE4 inhibition.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Like other amino acids, tryptophan is a zwitterion at physiological pH where the amino group is protonated (–NH+ 3; pKa = 9.39) and the carboxylic acid is deprotonated (–COO−; pKa = 2.38).
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Humans and many animals cannot synthesize tryptophan; they need to obtain it through their diet, making it an essential amino acid.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan is named after the digestive enzymes trypsin, which were used in its first isolation from casein proteins.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] It was assigned the one-letter symbol W based on the double ring being visually suggestive to the bulky letter.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Amino acids, including tryptophan, are used as building blocks in protein biosynthesis, and proteins are required to sustain life.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan is among the less common amino acids found in proteins, but it plays important structural or functional roles whenever it occurs.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] For instance, tryptophan and tyrosine residues play special roles in "anchoring" membrane proteins within the cell membrane.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan, along with other aromatic amino acids, is also important in glycan-protein interactions.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The disorder fructose malabsorption causes improper absorption of tryptophan in the intestine, reduced levels of tryptophan in the blood, and depression.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] In bacteria that synthesize tryptophan, high cellular levels of this amino acid activate a repressor protein, which binds to the trp operon.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Binding of this repressor to the tryptophan operon prevents transcription of downstream DNA that codes for the enzymes involved in the biosynthesis of tryptophan.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] So high levels of tryptophan prevent tryptophan synthesis through a negative feedback loop, and when the cell's tryptophan levels go down again, transcription from the trp operon resumes.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] This permits tightly regulated and rapid responses to changes in the cell's internal and external tryptophan levels.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Institute of Medicine set a Recommended Dietary Allowance (RDA) of 5 mg/kg body weight/day of tryptophan for adults 19 years and over.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan is present in most protein-based foods or dietary proteins.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] It is particularly plentiful in chocolate, oats, dried dates, milk, yogurt, cottage cheese, red meat, eggs, fish, poultry, sesame, legumes such as chickpeas and soybeans, almonds, sunflower seeds, pumpkin seeds, hemp seeds, buckwheat, spirulina, and peanuts.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Contrary to the popular belief that cooked turkey contains an abundance of tryptophan, the tryptophan content in turkey is typical of poultry.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Because tryptophan is converted into 5-hydroxytryptophan (5-HTP) which is then converted into the neurotransmitter serotonin, it has been proposed that consumption of tryptophan or 5-HTP may improve depression symptoms by increasing the level of serotonin in the brain.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan is sold over the counter in the United States (after being banned to varying extents between 1989 and 2005) and the United Kingdom as a dietary supplement for use as an antidepressant, anxiolytic, and sleep aid.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] It is also marketed as a prescription drug in some European countries for the treatment of major depression.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] There is evidence that blood tryptophan levels are unlikely to be altered by changing the diet, but consuming purified tryptophan increases the serotonin level in the brain, whereas eating foods containing tryptophan does not.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] In 2001 a Cochrane review of the effect of 5-HTP and tryptophan on depression was published.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The authors included only studies of a high rigor and included both 5-HTP and tryptophan in their review because of the limited data on either.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Of 108 studies of 5-HTP and tryptophan on depression published between 1966 and 2000, only two met the authors' quality standards for inclusion, totaling 64 study participants.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The use of tryptophan as an adjunctive therapy in addition to standard treatment for mood and anxiety disorders is not supported by the scientific evidence.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The American Academy of Sleep Medicine's 2017 clinical practice guidelines recommended against the use of tryptophan in the treatment of insomnia due to poor effectiveness.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Potential side effects of tryptophan supplementation include nausea, diarrhea, drowsiness, lightheadedness, headache, dry mouth, blurred vision, sedation, euphoria, and nystagmus (involuntary eye movements).
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan taken as a dietary supplement (such as in tablet form) has the potential to cause serotonin syndrome when combined with antidepressants of the MAOI or SSRI class or other strongly serotonergic drugs.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Because tryptophan supplementation has not been thoroughly studied in a clinical setting, its interactions with other drugs are not well known.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The isolation of tryptophan was first reported by Frederick Hopkins in 1901.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Hopkins recovered tryptophan from hydrolysed casein, recovering 4–8 g of tryptophan from 600 g of crude casein.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan is not synthesized from simpler substances in humans and other animals and is sourced from dietary intake of tryptophan-containing proteins.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Plants and microorganisms commonly synthesize tryptophan from shikimic acid or anthranilate.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan biosynthesis starts with the condensation of anthranilate with phosphoribosylpyrophosphate (PRPP), generating pyrophosphate as a by-product.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The ring of the ribose moiety is opened and subjected to reductive decarboxylation, producing indole-3-glycerol phosphate; this, in turn, is transformed into indole.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] In the last step, tryptophan synthase catalyzes the formation of tryptophan from indole and the amino acid serine.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The industrial production of tryptophan is also biosynthetic and is based on the fermentation of serine and indole using either wild-type or genetically modified bacteria such as *B. amyloliquefaciens*, *B. subtilis*, *C. glutamicum* or *E. coli*.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] These strains carry mutations that prevent the reuptake of aromatic amino acids or multiple/overexpressed trp operons.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The conversion is catalyzed by the enzyme tryptophan synthase.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] There was a large outbreak of eosinophilia-myalgia syndrome (EMS) in the U.S. in 1989, with more than 1,500 cases reported to the CDC and at least 37 deaths.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] After preliminary investigation revealed that the outbreak was linked to intake of tryptophan, the U.S.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) recalled tryptophan supplements in 1989 and banned most public sales in 1990, with other countries following suit.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Subsequent studies suggested that EMS was linked to specific batches of L-tryptophan supplied by a single large Japanese manufacturer, Showa Denko.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] It eventually became clear that recent batches of Showa Denko's L-tryptophan were contaminated by trace impurities, which were subsequently thought to be responsible for the 1989 EMS outbreak.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] However, other evidence suggests that tryptophan itself may be a potentially major contributory factor in EMS.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] There are also claims that a precursor reached sufficient concentrations to form a toxic dimer.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The FDA loosened its restrictions on sales and marketing of tryptophan in February 2001, but continued to limit the importation of tryptophan not intended for an exempted use until 2005.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Those calling for purity monitoring have, in turn, been criticized as anti-GMO activists who overlook possible non-GMO causes of contamination and threaten the development of biotech.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] A common assertion in the US and the UK is that heavy consumption of turkey meat—as seen during Thanksgiving and Christmas—results in drowsiness, due to high levels of tryptophan contained in turkey.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] However, the amount of tryptophan in turkey is comparable with that of other meats.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Drowsiness after eating may be caused by other foods eaten with the turkey, particularly carbohydrates.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Ingestion of a meal rich in carbohydrates triggers the release of insulin.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Insulin in turn stimulates the uptake of large neutral branched-chain amino acids (BCAA), but not tryptophan, into muscle, increasing the ratio of tryptophan to BCAA in the blood stream.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The resulting increased tryptophan ratio reduces competition at the large neutral amino acid transporter (which transports both BCAA and aromatic amino acids), resulting in more uptake of tryptophan across the blood–brain barrier into the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Once in the CSF, tryptophan is converted into serotonin in the raphe nuclei by the normal enzymatic pathway.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The resultant serotonin is further metabolised into the hormone melatonin—which is an important mediator of the circadian rhythm—by the pineal gland.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Hence, these data suggest that "feast-induced drowsiness"—or postprandial somnolence—may be the result of a heavy meal rich in carbohydrates, which indirectly increases the production of melatonin in the brain, and thereby promotes sleep.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] In 1912 Felix Ehrlich demonstrated that yeast metabolizes the natural amino acids essentially by splitting off carbon dioxide and replacing the amino group with a hydroxyl group.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] By this reaction, tryptophan gives rise to tryptophol.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan affects brain serotonin synthesis when given orally in a purified form and is used to modify serotonin levels for research.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Low brain serotonin level is induced by administration of tryptophan-poor protein in a technique called acute tryptophan depletion.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Studies using this method have evaluated the effect of serotonin on mood and social behavior, finding that serotonin reduces aggression and increases agreeableness.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan produces the head-twitch response (HTR) in rodents when administered at sufficiently high doses.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] The HTR is induced by serotonergic psychedelics like lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD) and psilocybin and is a behavioral proxy of psychedelic effects.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan is converted into the trace amine tryptamine and tryptamine is *N*-methylated by indolethylamine *N*-methyltransferase (INMT) into *N*-methyltryptamine (NMT) and *N*,*N*-dimethyltryptamine (DMT), which are known serotonergic psychedelics.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Tryptophan is an important intrinsic fluorescent probe (amino acid), which can be used to estimate the nature of the microenvironment around the tryptophan residue.
[src:tryptophan/tryptophan] Most of the intrinsic fluorescence emissions of a folded protein are due to excitation of tryptophan residues.
